		<h2>Topic</h2>
		Learning topics are grouped by category and classification and have a volunteer team. Details can be added about the specific focus in that topic
		<ul>
			<li><b>Course:</b> View available courses in the topic, and suggest new courses</li>
			<li><b>Bookmark:</b> List of memebers interested in the topic. Can be used to form learning teams</li>
		</ul>
		<p>
		<h3>Notes</h3>
		<ul>
			<li>Topic teams will be (later) changed from single leader to discovery and training teams</li>
		</ul>
		</p>

		<h2>Course</h2>
		Quite a few details are required while adding a course. This is to allow better understanding and easier search. 
		<ul>
			<li>Course name and details as provided in the MOOC website. Details should crisply indicate purpose and depth</li>
			<li>Accurate representation of estimated time and difficulty level. Effort should generally indicate number of weeks, and number of hours per week</li>
			<li>Cost of accessing the course material and tests, and any additional cost for optionally getting certified</li>
			<li>University whose staff is offering the course, to indicate quality. Do not enter MOOC website or video website name. For miscellaeous trainings, it could be software vendor, training vendor or an individual</li>
			<li>If the course is available on a schedule, mention dates in the details</li>
			<li style="color: blue"> Enter each URL as a separate course. There are options to link courses into a specialization</li>
			<li style="color: blue"> Course credits will be assigned by Leads based on time estimate and difficulty</li>
		</ul>

		Sub-courses can be linked under a specialization/curriculum type of course, so that members can choose to complete the whole sepcialization (generally with certification cost), or select only a few of the courses.
		<p>
		All members who are interested in, and currently undergoing, or have completed the course are listed. Average user rating is displayed to understand quality of the course material
		</p>

		<h2>Subscription</h2> 
		<ul>
			<li><b>Interested:</b>Bookmark the course for later. Useful to find interest in certifications. Rating not required at this time</li>
			<li><b>In Progress:</b>Started work on the source. Rating not required at this time</li>
			<li><b>Completed:</b>Successfully completed the course. Provide rating and any feedback</li>
			<li><b>Recommended:</b>Recommend the course for others. Should recommend only after completing the course. Feedback is required.</li>
			<li><b>Certified:</b>Completed the (optional) certification as well. Do not use recommended if certified</li>
		</ul>

		<h2>Category and Classification</h2>
		Categories and Classifications are helpful for easy search. New entries can be added, and existing ones can be renamed. Browse through the category/classification detail screen to find listed topics and the courses available

